Primary outcomes of interest included the prevalence of hyperglycemia and mortality. Causes of death were classified according to the Coding of Death in HIV(CoDe) protocol.","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6bhj1","text":"","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"31kmk","text":"Results","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":7}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4uapq","text":"Our study included 2914 people living with HIV. Two hundred and forty-two (8.3%)patients had hyperglycemia, with an increasing prevalence by age. Three hundred one(9.7%) participants died over the median 3.71 (IQR: 2.14-5.37) years of follow-up. Among these, 139 (46.2%) were due to AIDS-related causes, 123 (40.9%) – were due to non-AIDS causes, and in 39 (12.9%) cases, the cause of death could not be determined. Overall, the cohort contributed to 11,148 person-years offollow-up (PYFU), translating into a mortality rate of 2.70 deaths per 100 PYFU. The mortalityrate was significantly higher among individuals with hyperglycemia - 11.17 deaths per 100PYFU vs 2.07 deaths per100 PYFU amongnormoglycemicpatients(p\u003c0.0001).\nConclusions","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":726,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7c096","text":"Hyperglycemia was associated with increased odds of mortality.
